<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911121-0101</DOCNO><DOCID>911121-0101.</DOCID><HL>   Fannie Mae, Freddie Mac   Boost Limit on Mortgages</HL><DATE>11/21/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C18</SO><CO>   FNM FRE</CO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>DIVERSIFIED FINANCIAL SERVICES, CREDIT INSTITUTIONS (FIS)MORTGAGES, MORTGAGE-BACKED SECURITIES (MOR)</IN><NS>MORTGAGES, MORTGAGE RATES (MOR)</NS><RE>ALASKA (AK)DISTRICT OF COLUMBIA (DC)HAWAII (HI)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   WASHINGTON -- The nation's two largest buyers ofresidential mortgages increased the limit on thesingle-family mortgages they will purchase to $202,300, areflection of the moderate rise in national home values overthe past year. Federal National Mortgage Association andFederal Home Loan Mortgage Corp., known respectively asFannie Mae and Freddie Mac, both increased the upper limit onconforming loans by 5.8%, from $191,250 in 1991.   The change will afford purchasers of single-family homeswho take out mortgages of between $191,250 and $202,300 thebenefit of rates about 0.5 percentage point lower than onlarger loans, which are called jumbo loans. Jumbo loanstypically carry higher interest rates because lenders cannotsell them to the two government-chartered companies, whichpackage them for resale to investors as securities.</LP><TEXT>   Both companies change their loan limits each year inresponse to changes in average home prices reported by theFederal Housing Finance Board. Similarly, loan limits wereincreased on two-family, three-family and four-family homes.The limits in Alaska and Hawaii will be 50% higher than inthe rest of the nation.</TEXT></DOC>